│ THOUGHT                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The user wants me to fix a crash in the LLVM SLP vectorizer.                                                                                                                             │
│ The crash is an assertion failure in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp:3711`:                                                                                             │
│ `Assertion '(hasFullVectorsOrPowerOf2(*TTI, getValueType(VL.front()), VL.size()) || ReuseShuffleIndices.empty()) && "Reshuffling scalars not yet supported for nodes with padding"'      │
│ failed.`                                                                                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ This assertion is inside `BoUpSLP::newTreeEntry`. It's intended to prevent attempts to reshuffle scalars for vectorization candidates that require padding (i.e., the number of elements │
│ is not a power of two and not a legal vector size).                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The reproducer shows the SLP vectorizer attempting to vectorize a group of four `phi` nodes. The number of elements is 4, which is a power of two. The type is `i64`. A `<4 x i64>`      │
│ vector is generally legal on x86-64. Therefore, `hasFullVectorsOrPowerOf2` should return true, and the assertion should not fire.                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The problem lies in how the vectorization candidate is constructed. The SLP vectorizer is trying to vectorize the `phi` nodes: `%storemerge64`, `%storemerge63`, `%storemerge62`,        │
│ `%storemerge`. These form a group of 4 scalars.                                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The incoming values for these `phi` nodes from block `%bb2` are `%imin.2.us`, `%jmin.2.us`, `%imax.2.us`, `%jmax.2.us`. These are results of `select` instructions. The vectorizer will  │
│ recursively try to vectorize these `select` instructions.                                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The `select` instructions are:                                                                                                                                                           │
│ `%imax.2.us = select i1 %cmp14.us, i64 0, i64 0`                                                                                                                                         │
│ `%jmax.2.us = select i1 %cmp14.us, i64 0, i64 0`                                                                                                                                         │
│ `%imin.2.us = select i1 %cmp13.us, i64 0, i64 0`                                                                                                                                         │
│ `%jmin.2.us = select i1 %cmp13.us, i64 0, i64 0`                                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The vectorizer will group these into two sets based on their conditions:                                                                                                                 │
│ 1. `%imax.2.us`, `%jmax.2.us` (condition `%cmp14.us`)                                                                                                                                    │
│ 2. `%imin.2.us`, `%jmin.2.us` (condition `%cmp13.us`)                                                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ When `buildTree_rec` processes the `select` instructions, it groups them by their condition. It finds two groups of two `selects`. It then tries to build a tree for each group. For the │
│ first group (`%imax.2.us`, `%jmax.2.us`), `VL.size()` is 2. `i64` is the type. `<2 x i64>` is a legal vector type, so `hasFullVectorsOrPowerOf2` is true.                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ However, the conditions `%cmp14.us` and `%cmp13.us` are results of `fcmp` on `x86_fp80`. The `x86_fp80` type is not a legal vector element type on most targets. When the vectorizer     │
│ tries to analyze the `fcmp` instructions, it finds that it cannot form a vector of `x86_fp80`.                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The issue seems to be that the vectorizer attempts to build a tree for a sub-group of scalars (size 2 in this case) but uses `ReuseShuffleIndices` that were computed for the original   │
│ group of 4 scalars. When `buildTree_rec` is called for the sub-group of two `selects`, `ReuseShuffleIndices` is not empty, but `hasFullVectorsOrPowerOf2` might be evaluated for the     │
│ sub-group's operands.                                                                                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The `fcmp` instructions are identical for the pairs of `selects`.                                                                                                                        │
│ `%cmp14.us = fcmp ogt x86_fp80 0xK00000000000000000000, 0xK00000000000000000000`                                                                                                         │
│ `%cmp13.us = fcmp olt x86_fp80 0xK00000000000000000000, 0xK00000000000000000000`                                                                                                         │
│ The vectorizer will try to vectorize these. It will see two `fcmp` instructions. The operands are constants of type `x86_fp80`. The vectorizer will try to build a `<2 x x86_fp80>`      │
│ vector of these constants. `isLegalElementType(x86_fp80)` will be false. `hasFullVectorsOrPowerOf2` for a vector of size 2 of this type will be false.                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The problem is that `buildTree_rec` is called recursively on a smaller vector (`VL` of size 2), but `ReuseShuffleIndices` (which is non-empty) was computed for the original vector of   │
